Not sure if you see old comments anymore. I have been making my way through your series, oldest to newest, and was absolutely overjoyed when my husband began joining me for my morning practice halfway through yoga camp. But then in Revolution, the practices have included more singing (please, no more singing) and have gotten more philosophical with less time to just be quiet and reflect. I honestly show up every day to get a physical and mental break, and the constant talking can be distracting sometimes. My husband is no longer interested because it was too much and he wasn‚Äôt able to focus. I know you provide this service for us for free and I am so, so grateful. I just wish there was more quiet time, with words for pose instruction and direction instead of so much in between. Some of your videos, the ones where you do the voice overlay, are so incredible bc it‚Äôs only the words pertinent to the poses instead of side stories and song references. Those practices are so powerful. Hoping your next series and the ones after are more focused on that. Hope I didn‚Äôt upset you with my critique, but I just wish the practices were a bit more quiet so we can self-reflect.

I've noticed something interesting on my yoga journey. On the days I don't make it to the mat, I'm often not very nice to myself when it comes to my body. I don't tend to think nice things about my lower belly, specifically. But on the days that I make it to the mat, when I take some time just to tend to myself, I'm reminded of how strong I've become and how my center carries me throughout my whole life. I am reminded to do yoga, not because of how it will make me look, but to see what my body can do and how it can feel.

I'm a disabled veteran, been hit by 2 cars and been in 5 major car accidents. My spine is jacked.  I feel that these yoga practices have improved my way of life. I raise my son full time on my own and this has been a blessing. I am able to go out and throw a baseball or shoot some hoops with him again. My posture has improved dramatically. Not to mention my pain level has decreased.  I am able to do resistance training again because of the foundational strength that yoga has provided me. I honestly would have never thought in a million years that I would be doing yoga and actually admitting to it. Now if I had to choose one workout to do for the rest of my life it would be yoga. Thank you, Adriene for making these videos that are simple to follow along with. I don't even have to look up at the screen most of the time because your verbal cues are on point, and your jokes are entertaining as well. I'm grateful that I let my ego go and stepped outside of my comfort zone. Thanks again, you rock!

Hi Adriene!

I've been following your videos for a few years now (did the original 30 days of yoga and yoga camp), and I want to tell you how grateful I am to have found this channel. Aside from financial restraints, I also deal with severe anxiety that makes it extremely difficult to go to classes with other people.  Following along with your videos has made me feel like I am in my own personal yoga class, and the longer I've been watching the better I have gotten to know the teacher (e.g.-all the little inside jokes). What I like best is that you have something for everyone, or every feeling, every body part, every part of the day. I've recommended you to the girls in my therapy group and to my 6' 200+ pound cousin. I've never commented before, but I just wanted you to know how grateful I am to have you in my home. You've brought a shining light into my life, especially now when the current political climate of the country is grim.

Also, I know you are a musical fan, and I don't know if you're familiar with Hamilton, but every time you say "rise up," I wanna sing, "when you're living on you're knees you rise up! Tell your sister that she's gotta rise up."

I was very grateful yesterday that I've been showing up and doing the work - my building supplies arrived a couple of hours earlier than scheduled, when I was still out feeding livestock, and although the delivery driver kindly unloaded it outside the house rather than just driving away with it, it meant I had to shift, by myself, 6 sheets of 8x4 plasterboard (drywall) and 30 sheets of 8x2 chipboard in a 35mph breeze that turned them all into sails.  Given the plasterboard sheets weighed 26kg (57lbs) each and I'm 5'5" and weigh 145lbs, it was a challenge, but thanks to the all the yoga I found that not only did I have the strength and discipline to get the job done in 45 minutes, but my muscles haven't felt it too badly - if this had happened last month, I wouldn't be able to move today!
